In your own words, explain why the secret number kept changing in the original app.
The secret number kept changing in the original app because of how Streamlit reruns the script every time a user interacts with the interface. 
When a button is clicked or a value is entered, Streamlit reruns the entire script from the top. 
If the secret number is generated normally in the script without storing it, a new number can be created each time the script reruns. 
This makes the game inconsistent because the number the player is trying to guess may change between guesses. 
As a result, the player could never actually reach the correct answer.

How would you explain Streamlit "reruns" and session state to a friend who has never used Streamlit?
I would explain Streamlit reruns and session state to a friend by saying that Streamlit works like refreshing the program every time you interact with the page. 
Instead of updating only one part of the app, the whole script runs again from the beginning. 
Session state is like a memory that stores important values so they don’t reset during these reruns. 
By saving variables such as the secret number or attempt count in session state, the program can remember them between interactions. 
Without session state, the game would lose track of important information every time something changes.

What change did you make that finally gave the game a stable secret number?
The change that finally gave the game a stable secret number was storing the value inside st.session_state. 
Instead of generating a new number every time the script ran, the code first checks whether "secret" already exists in the session state. 
If it does not exist, the game generates a random number and saves it there. Because the value is stored in session state, it stays the same across multiple guesses. 
This allowed the player to keep guessing the same number until they won or ran out of attempts.

